Sorry that expression from the FAQ should have read:

(species.MeanFitness / population.TotalOfSpeciesMeanFitness) * requiredPopulationSize



Colin Green wrote:

&gt;I&#39;ve come against a small problem with the fitness sharing technique so 
&gt;I would like to ask how others are handling this...
&gt;
&gt;I started by calculating the size of a species as follows:
&gt;
&gt;   species.TotalAdjustedFitness / population.MeanAdjustedFitness
&gt;
&gt;This I think will introduce a problem whereby the total size of the 
&gt;population will have a tendency to shrink or grow depending on whether 
&gt;you round the result of this expression up or down. ok  When I wrote the 
&gt;evolution algorithm last year I had though of this which is why I had 
&gt;chosen to cull the population as a whole back to it&#39;s proper size 
&gt;(instead of per species) which was not such a great idea :) Anyway the 
&gt;NEAT FAQ suggests using the following expression instead:
&gt;
&gt;   species.MeanFitness / population.TotalOfSpeciesMeanFitness
&gt;
&gt;Which is great except I just noticed that if all of the organisms have 
&gt;fitness 0 then I will end up with a population size of 0. I realise this 
&gt;is a special case, you would normaly see some minimal fitness in the 
&gt;initial population and hence no problem.
&gt;
&gt;Possible solutions then.
&gt;1) Precalculate the size of the population, test for the zero case and 
&gt;if so then keep the original species sizes.
&gt;2) Define a minimum fitness greater than 0. This is a bit bit of a hack 
&gt;though really.
&gt;3) Keep generating initial populations until a none zero fitness occurs.
&gt;
&gt;Thoughts?
&gt;
&gt;Colin.
